{"key":"processedPost-8906197","value":{"id":8906197,"first":8904864,"last":8906197,"when":1221063056,"utime":"09/10/08 07:10 PM","cleanedPost":"A search for hay should have returned many threads with lots of reasons not to use it.&nbsp; The seeds are a major reason as they'll contaminate with green molds.&nbsp; Straw is better also because it's hollow and that gives lots of places for mycelium to colonize, as well as a moisture reservoir to support massive flushes, which hay can't provide.&nbsp; Some of the biggest mushrooms we've ever seen around here were grown on straw, so that makes moot the point about 'nutrients'.&nbsp; Below is a micrograph of a cross section of straw, so you can see what I mean.<br />RR<br /><a href=\"https://files.shroomery.org/files/07-006/108452877-SEM_of_Straw.jpg\" class=\"highslide\" onclick=\"return hs.expand(this,{slideshowGroup:'hsg1'})\" target=\"_blank\"><img style=\"max-width:192px;height:auto;\" src=\"/forums/thumbs/07-006/108452877-thumb_SEM_of_Straw.jpg\"></a>"}}